What is CACTUS?CACTUS is a non-profit Ukrainian NGO that promotes civil activism and responsibility among youths by providing them with the knowledge, tools and support necessary for making a positive social change. With almost 10 years of work behind our back, the NGO aims to expand a network of enthusiastic and motivated people ready to make their contribution to the development of Ukraine.How does it work?In addition to the year-round educational program, CACTUS holds an annual summer 10-day forum for 60 Ukrainian teenagers aged 13-18 coming from all over the country. Since we strive to help them identify the ways to contribute to their communities and give the tools needed for it, the CACTUS Forum has the following goals:
to develop communication and leadership skills. All the participants are to attend a Team Building session every day. In this way they study the best communication and coworking strategies as well as learn to identify and use their strengths so as to achieve the common team's goal in the long run;
to develop critical thinking and research skills. All the participants are to attend a Project Management session every day. Here the participants go over every single step of project creation: starting with identifying problems and their causes all the way up to budget and action plan; all the project ideas are then presented on the 10th day of the Forum;
to develop flexibility and creativity. Electives classes in Art (e.g. creative writing, photography) and Science (e.g. programming, model thinking) are provided in order to make it possible for the teenagers to think outside the box;

to bring up such topics as diversity, inclusion, and gender equality. CACTUS does not discriminate people on the grounds of sex, sexual orientation, race or ethnicity, physical abilities. That is why a Diversity Session - meetings with people ready to share their personal stories of dealing with the above mentioned issues - is held in order to promote diversity and inclusion;

to share volunteering, educational, and professional opportunities. CACTUS will invite speakers from such spheres as technology, media, human rights, education, and urban space, all of whom are eager to provide the participants with guidelines as to where they can seek development while still being school and university students;
to create a network of young leaders with a clear vision of possible changes in their communities; CACTUS provides a perfect environment for establishing valuable contacts with potential sponsors, mentors, and future team members for the community projects.

The biggest outcome of the CACTUS Forum will be the very first community service projects created and implemented by teenagers. With the participants coming from all over Ukraine, the estimated number of people affected by the projects will be as high as 1000.CACTUS has been making changes in the Ukrainian community for almost 10 years. That is why holding the 10th anniversary Forum will be the direct proof of the impact it has done and a unique opportunity for at least 60 more Ukrainian youths to become leaders in their home communities.Why do we do it?We believe that even though it is impossible to tackle all the world issues at once, each of us can still think globally and act locally. CACTUS gives the necessary skills and tools to first analyze and then address the educational, ecological, and social issues Ukraine is facing today in the most effective way. When and where?This year the CACTUS Forum will take place in the city of Ternopil (Western Ukraine) on July 20-29.

July 17-19 - training for volunteers;

July 20-29 - the Forum;

July 28 - the 10th CACTUS Forum anniversary for the alumni of all the previous years;

July 30 - evaluation of the Forum.
Why do we need funding?CACTUS is growing bigger every year, expanding its staff team and developing a better teaching quality. The NGO has been functioning for 9 years thanks to small grants, in-kind donations, and local fundraising, being supported by people who are truly dedicated to the CACTUS mission - making a change. However, the funds the NGO possesses right now are not enough to hold the 10th anniversary Forum and implement the whole Forum curriculum.That is why CACTUS needs additional funding for:accommodation. 60 participants - $4/day - $40/10 days - $2,400 in total;25 staff members (Ukrainian and international volunteers/trainers) - $4/day - $40/10 days - $1,000 in total;20 guest speakers - $4/day - $80 in total.meals.​60 participants - $5/day - $50/10 days - $3,000 in total;25 staff members (Ukrainian and international volunteers/trainers) - $5/day - $50/10 days - $1,250 in total;20 guest speakers - $5/day - $100 in total.
other expenditures (e.g. transport, venue rental, media equipment, stationery, printouts).All the costs add up to $8,000. However, we set a goal of $7,000 since we will cover the remaining $1,000 with the help of local fundraising and our partner organizations that can provide partial monetary (Rotary Club) and material (Morshinska, local IT companies) support.​Where will the funds go if we don't reach our entire goal? CACTUS will fundraise the remaining sum locally (e.g. contacting local partner organizations and sponsors, organizing charitable events, selling CACTUS merchandise) and will use all the available funds (from the Indiegogo donations and local fundraising) for the Forum expenditures. What can you get for contributing to CACTUS?We appreciate your contribution to CACTUS, and that is why besides successful community projects implemented by our participants, we offer the following items that help us promote CACTUS both directly and indirectly:

report on the funds use for all backers;

CACTUS stickers for $10+ contribution;

CACTUS bag for $25+ contribution;

CACTUS notebook for $50+ contribution;

CACTUS T-shirt for $100+ contribution;

CACTUS sweatshirt for $300+ contribution.

What about challenges?It is not easy to bring together 60 teenagers in summer and encourage them to work, but it is even harder to ensure the sustainability and lasting impact of the Forum after the event itself. That is why in order to make these 10 days count, a mentor is assigned to each project group according to the topic at hand. A mentor is not only a teacher, but also a wise friend who supports the participants during the whole period of project implementation. In this way we can keep in touch with all the Forum participants when they go home, giving them constructive feedback and making sure they are working on their projects.Why is it important?CACTUS is all about people and growth. Over the 10 days spent at the Forum the teenagers discover new facets of their personality as well as numerous issues relevant for Ukraine and the world, such as environment, inclusion, education, and human rights. Getting up-to-date information about these topics, participants go on to address them in their projects. Moreover, by the end of the Forum they have complete profiles of their projects: goals and objectives, budget, action and sustainability plans. Once the Forum is over, there is but one step left - make the project a reality.CACTUS brings not the destination but the starting point to the lives of the people engaged. Not only do the participants become leaders in their communities, but they also enter leading Ukrainian and international universities, build successful careers and keep on supporting CACTUS. Thus, over the 9 years of CACTUS work

11,000 people have participated in CACTUS activities;

130 community projects have been implemented;

600 volunteers have contributed to CACTUS (among them volunteers from 5 continents);

1,009 teenagers benefited from CACTUS in 2017.

 Some examples of successful projects? !НАВАЖСЯ! (literally: !I DARE YOU!)One of a number of projects successfully implemented by the participants of the CACTUS Forum 2017 is "!НАВАЖСЯ!" (literally: "!I DARE YOU!"). Olena Kyslovska (16 y.o.) and Polina Chesnokova (14 y.o.) tackled the topic of inclusion in Ukraine. The girls worked with a group of students from a specialized school for children with special needs in Kyiv for 2 months. Over this time Olena and Polina have held 6 seminars, 2 workshops, 1 social event and 1 meeting with a guest speaker from the field. The girls covered such topics as leadership, team work, dealing with fear and anxiety, educational opportunities, and, most importantly, showed the children with special needs that the Ukrainian society is inclusion-friendly and there are a lot of opportunities for them to get involved! Olena and Polina have won a Diamond Challenge for High School Entrepreneurs award and are planning to expand their project.The project FB page: https://www.facebook.com/navazhsya/Un-Bottom Waste BinKateryna Malkina (16 y.o.) from Mariupol has created an ecological project dealing with an innovative way of plastic utilization by one of larvae species. Her project consists of 2 directions: scientific and social. Kateryna is working on the project in her school lab, examining the behavior of larvae in different environments over a specific period of time. She has also held a meeting with students at one of local schools where she spoke about her project as well as about the environmental challenges and our role in them in the context of Ukraine and the world. Kateryna has won a number of scientific contests in such countries as Ukraine, the Netherlands, the USA, Brazil, presenting her project on the international level.Have we missed anything?The only thing CACTUS lacks right now is YOUR contribution. Think about it - you can skip having a cup of coffee today and cover a $5-meal for one CACTUS participant!Are there other ways to help?There are for sure. You can:

apply for a CACTUS trainer's position and join the international staff members team for the CACTUS Forum 2018;

share the CACTUS campaign via social media and encourage your friends to support us;
let us know about organizations interested in this kind of projects.
